INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '4d5ee90b-0ca4-47a7-b1aa-98e310d65e03',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Polars describe() and null_count() — Profile Any Dataset in Seconds$escape$,
  $escape$Polars gives you fast dataset profiling without reaching for external libraries. Start with df.describe() — it returns count, null_count, mean, std, min, max, and median for every column in a single pass, leveraging Polars' multi-threaded engine. Unlike pandas, this runs in parallel across columns automatically.

For missing value analysis, df.null_count() returns a single-row DataFrame with null counts per column — far cleaner than chaining .is_null().sum(). Combine it with df.schema to quickly flag columns where nulls exceed a threshold.

To understand distributions, use df.select(pl.col('price').quantile(q)) across multiple quantiles, or value_counts() for categorical columns. The n_unique() expression helps identify low-cardinality columns suitable for encoding.

For a full profiling pass, chain these in a single select() context. Polars' lazy evaluation means you can build the entire profile as a LazyFrame and call .collect() once, avoiding redundant scans over the same data.$escape$,
  $escape$import polars as pl

df = pl.read_csv("dataset.csv")

# Full statistical summary
print(df.describe())

# Null analysis per column
nulls = df.null_count()
print(nulls)

# Distribution profiling in one pass
profile = df.select(
    pl.all().n_unique().name.suffix("_nunique"),
    pl.all().null_count().name.suffix("_nulls"),
    pl.selectors.numeric().mean().name.suffix("_mean"),
    pl.selectors.numeric().std().name.suffix("_std"),
)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
