INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a30b8e3f-3dfa-44b7-9bb7-ee77645f42d3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Polars scan_parquet() — Process 100GB Files Without Blowing Up RAM$escape$,
  $escape$Polars already handles larger-than-RAM datasets natively through its lazy API — no Dask required. The key is scan_parquet() (or scan_csv()), which creates a LazyFrame that pushes predicates and projections down to the I/O layer, reading only what's needed.

For truly massive datasets, combine lazy scanning with streaming execution via collect(streaming=True). This processes data in batches internally, keeping memory flat. Pair it with sink_parquet() to write results incrementally without materializing the full frame.

Sampling is straightforward: after a lazy scan, chain .collect().sample(n=10_000) or use .head()/slice() in the lazy plan for deterministic subsets. For stratified sampling, group_by then apply sample per group.

When to graduate to Spark? When your workload is distributed across nodes — Polars is single-node only. If your data fits on one machine (even 500GB+ with streaming), Polars will outperform Spark dramatically. The real boundary isn't data size, it's cluster necessity: joins across partitioned datasets on multiple machines.$escape$,
  $escape$import polars as pl

# Lazy scan — reads only 'user_id' and 'event' columns,
# filters at the I/O level, never loads full file
result = (
    pl.scan_parquet("events/**/*.parquet")
    .filter(pl.col("event") == "purchase")
    .select("user_id", "event", "amount")
    .group_by("user_id")
    .agg(pl.col("amount").sum().alias("total_spend"))
    .sort("total_spend", descending=True)
    .collect(streaming=True)
)

# Stratified sample: 100 users per region
sampled = result.group_by("region").map_groups(
    lambda df: df.sample(n=min(100, len(df)))
)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
